# Reference accessed: 2026-05-30 via gh api.
#
# lem-language-server is the **Lem editor's Language
# Server Protocol implementation** — provides LSP
# support for the Lem Emacs-like editor written in
# Common Lisp.  Pivots from Racket racket/cmdline
# (R290 cassius) into the **Common Lisp language
# tooling cluster**.  Sister to SBCL, Quicklisp,
# clingon (alternative CL CLI library).  **MAJOR
# MILESTONE**: corpus's **first documented Common
# Lisp CLI** — adds Common Lisp to the cross-language
# CLI taxonomy (30 library variants now).
#
# Critical extraction note: lem-language-server uses
# **`command-line-arguments`** library (CLi for short)
# — corpus's **first documented Common Lisp CLI**.
# `command-line-arguments` is **one of** the standard
# CL CLI libraries (others include `clingon`,
# `unix-opts`, `defcommand`).  Used by Lem,
# screenshotbot, and many Common Lisp tooling
# projects.  Extends the **cross-language CLI
# taxonomy** to THIRTY library variants: Rust (6), Go
# (4), Python (3), Crystal OptionParser (R269),
# Haskell optparse-applicative (R270), OCaml Cmdliner
# (R271), C POSIX getopt (R272), Java picocli (R276),
# Kotlin clikt (R277), Scala decline (R278), Dart
# args (R279), Ruby OptionParser (R280), Perl
# Getopt::Long (R281), PHP Symfony Console (R282),
# Swift ArgumentParser (R283), F# Argu (R284), Lua
# argparse (R285), C# System.CommandLine (R286), Nim
# parseopt (R287), Zig std.process.argsAlloc (R288),
# D std.getopt (R289), Racket racket/cmdline (R290),
# **Common Lisp command-line-arguments** (R291 —
# NEW).  **MAJOR PATTERN MILESTONE**: 30 cross-
# language CLI library variants documented.
#
# Critical extraction note: lem-language-server uses
# **`defparameter *command-line-spec*` LIST-BASED
# CLI SPEC stored as Lisp data** at cli.lisp:6-26 —
# the CLI specification is a regular Lisp data
# structure (a list of lists), NOT a macro or
# compiled struct.  Each option is a list `(("name"
# #\short-char) :type X :optional t :documentation
# "...")`.  Documents the **data-as-CLI-spec
# pattern** — distinct from Racket's macro-based DSL
# (R290 cassius), Java picocli annotations (R276),
# and Swift property wrappers (R283).  In Common
# Lisp, the CLI spec is FIRST-CLASS DATA that can be
# inspected, modified, or generated at runtime.  Plus
# the spec is bound to a global parameter, allowing
# multiple functions (`main`, `command-line-error`)
# to reference the same spec.  Corpus's **first
# documented data-as-CLI-spec pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: lem-language-server uses
# **Lisp CHARACTER LITERAL `#\h`** at cli.lisp:25
# for the SHORT NAME — `("help" #\h)` is the option
# name list: long name string + short character.
# Common Lisp's `#\X` syntax is the character literal
# (e.g., `#\h` is the character 'h', not the string
# "h").  Documents the **Lisp character-literal for
# short flag** — distinct from Rust's `'h'` char
# literal (R260 dua uses `short = 'A'`), Ruby's
# string `"-h"` (R280 reek), and Perl's pipe-syntax
# `'h|help'` (R281 cpanm).  Lisp's character literal
# is type-distinct from strings.  Corpus's **first
# documented Lisp character-literal CLI pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: lem-language-server uses
# **DATA-DRIVEN DISPATCH** at cli.lisp:28-32 —
# `command-line-arguments:handle-command-line *spec*
# 'run-server :command-line args` passes the SPEC
# DATA + HANDLER SYMBOL + ARGS as a single function
# call.  The library handles parsing AND invokes
# the handler with the parsed values.  Documents the
# **data + handler-symbol dispatch pattern** —
# distinct from clap derive's struct-population
# (R247+) and from Click's decorator stack (R266
# uvicorn).  In Common Lisp, `'run-server` is a
# QUOTED SYMBOL that names the handler function; the
# library resolves it at runtime via `funcall`.
# Plus the handler signature `(&key tcp stdio (port
# 10007) log-file help)` uses Common Lisp **keyword
# arguments with defaults** — the parsed CLI values
# are passed as `:tcp t :port 10007 ...` keyword
# args.  Corpus's **first documented data-driven
# handler-symbol dispatch**.
#
# Critical extraction note: lem-language-server uses
# **runtime MUTEX validation** at cli.lisp:44-46 —
# `(when (and tcp stdio) (command-line-error "These
# arguments cannot be used together: (tcp, stdio)")
# (return-from run-server))` — the handler manually
# checks for incompatible flag combinations.
# Documents the **runtime cross-flag mutex pattern**
# — distinct from R250 sozo's clap `#[group(multiple
# = false)]` (declarative), R249 cairo-profiler's
# `conflicts_with` attribute (declarative), and
# Symfony Console's `@ArgGroup(exclusive = true)`
# (R276 checkstyle).  Common Lisp's approach uses
# IMPERATIVE if-checks in the handler — typical of
# data-driven CLI libraries that don't have
# declarative mutex support.  Plus the library
# (`command-line-arguments`) has no built-in mutex
# attribute; the developer encodes it manually.

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line

# 5 flags decoded source-direct from
# *command-line-spec* at cli.lisp:6-26.
_arguments -s -S \
  '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[display help]' \
  '(--tcp)--stdio[start the server with stdio (default; mutex with --tcp via runtime check)]' \
  '(--stdio)--tcp[start the server with TCP (mutex with --stdio via runtime check)]' \
  '--port=[port number for TCP (default: 10007)]:port:' \
  '--log-file=[file to output the log]:file:_files -g "*.log"'
